In C programming, an if/then statement is used to execute a block of code if a specified condition is true. Here are the steps to write an if/then statement in C:

1. Use the if keyword followed by a condition enclosed in parentheses.
2. If the condition is true, the block of code following the if statement will be executed.
3. Use the else keyword to specify an alternative block of code to be executed if the condition is false.
4. Use curly braces ({}) to enclose the blocks of code to be executed if the condition is true or false.

Here is an example of an if/then statement in C:

```
if (age >= 18) {
    printf("You are eligible to vote.");
} else {
    printf("You are not eligible to vote.");
}
```

In this example, the if/then statement checks if the age variable is greater than or equal to 18. If the condition is true, the first block of code will be executed, and the message "You are eligible to vote." will be printed. If the condition is false, the else block of code will be executed, and the message "You are not eligible to vote." will be printed.

Remember to always use curly braces to enclose the blocks of code to be executed if the condition is true or false. This will ensure that the code is executed correctly and avoid any unexpected behavior.
